{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "Do the rest from 1 to 10.   " }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 31 "Note:  it is possible to use a " }{TEXT 263 9 "for
 loop " }{TEXT -1 69 " to simplify this task since we are doing a repe
titive calculation.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 29 "Note:  Also, the
 the command " }{TEXT 265 6 "coeffs" }{TEXT -1 15 " unfortunately " }
{TEXT 266 8 "does not" }{TEXT -1 36 " pick off the coefficients in ord
er." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "The
 " }{TEXT 259 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 66 " gives a formula for
 finding the coefficients of the expansion of " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^
n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 10 "  for any " }{TEXT 
267 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 ".  It is relatively obvious that the coefficie
nt of  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "a^(n-k)*b^k;" "6#*&)%\"aG,&%\"nG\"\"\"%\"kG!
\"\"F()%\"bGF)F(" }{TEXT -1 19 "  for any value of " }{TEXT 268 1 "k" 
}{TEXT -1 11 " from 0 to " }{TEXT 269 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 46 " is given by
 the number of ways we can choose " }{TEXT 270 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 8 " of \+
the " }{TEXT 294 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 12 "'s from the " }{TEXT 271 1 "n" }
{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 295 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 20 "'s in the expansion " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)*(a+b)" "6#*&,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&F&,&F%F&F'F&F&" }
{TEXT -1 7 " ....( " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)" "6#,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF%" }
{TEXT -1 5 " ),  " }{TEXT 272 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 41 " times .   The numbe
r of combinations of " }{TEXT 273 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 18 " objects choosin
g " }{TEXT 274 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 12 " at a time, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "nCk" 
"6#%$nCkG" }{TEXT -1 27 ", is given by the formula  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "
nCk=n!/(k!*(n-k)!)" "6#/%$nCkG*&-%*factorialG6#%\"nG\"\"\"*&-F'6#%\"kG
F*-F'6#,&F)F*F.!\"\"F*F2" }{TEXT -1 2 " ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 261 10 "State the " }{TEXT 260 16 "Binomi
al Theorem" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 275 31 "and use Maple to demonstrat
e it" }{TEXT -1 1 "." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }{TEXT 297 220 "
performed above: for polynomials that have two terms the exponents and
 coeffeicents provide a factor list of all possible combinations and o
ccuring in palandromic patterns.(not a text book definition, but one a
s see it.)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 8 "Compute " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "su
m(binomial(n,k),k=0..n)" "6#-%$sumG6$-%)binomialG6$%\"nG%\"kG/F*;\"\"!
F)" }{TEXT -1 34 "  for n=1 to 10.  Here the symbol " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "
Sigma;" "6#%&SigmaG" }{TEXT -1 70 " (Greek letter Sigma) stands for su
m.   (See the worksheet SumSeq.mws)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
258 59 "What general formula do the above calculations in  suggest?" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 48 "number of factors is related to linear e
xponents" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 388 "2.  Pascal's Triangle.  Recall th
e definition of Pascal's Triangle.   Use Maple to construct the first \+
10 rows of Pascal's Triangle. (The trick will be to get the coefficien
ts to occur in the correct order.  The Maple command for generating a \+
sequence might be helpful. It is   seq(expression(i),i=m..n);   where \+
expression(i) is an expression with index i and m..n is a range of num
bers." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 "   " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 58 "for p from 0 to 10\ndo\nseq(coeff((a+1)^p,a,n), n=0..
p);\nod;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"\"\"" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "
" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"\"F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%\"\"\"\"
\"#F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6&\"\"\"\"\"$F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "
