{XPPMATH 20 "6(\"\"\"\"\"&\"#5F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "
6)\"\"\"\"\"'\"#:\"#?F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6*\"\"\"
\"\"(\"#@\"#NF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6+\"\"\"\"\")\"
#G\"#c\"#qF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6,\"\"\"\"\"*\"#O
\"#%)\"$E\"F'F&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6-\"\"\"\"#5\"#
X\"$?\"\"$5#\"$_#F'F&F%F$F#" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "
> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 214 "3.  Functions.  In this exericse we study the ba
sic properties of polynomials and rational functions.  Some revelant M
APLE commands will be   factor, expand, solve, fsolve, denom, numer, s
implify, subs,   ....... ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 171 "     The f
irst thing we need to learn is how to define a function.  There are tw
o ways, each with its own advantages and disadvantages.  First define \+
the polynomial p1 as " }{TEXT 282 2 "a " }{TEXT -1 1 "s" }{TEXT 283 
23 "ymbolic expression in x" }{TEXT -1 119 " in the following way:    \+
p1:=x^2-1;  (Note the colon before the =, this is always required when
 defining something.)  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p
1:=x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p1G,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"
\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 39 "     Now define the same polynomial as " }{TEXT 281 30 "an oper
ation on the variable x" }{TEXT -1 40 " in the following way:     p2:=
x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 12 "p2:x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }
}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#f*6#%\"xG6\"6$%)operatorG%&arrowGF&,&
*$)9$\"\"#\"\"\"F/F/!\"\"F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 257 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 190 "Try the following command sequences to
 see some of the differences in how MAPLE  treats these two definition
s.  As always record your observations and comments on the worksheet i
n text mode." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 
"" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%\"xG\"
\"#\"\"\"F(F(!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p2;" }
}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#%#p2G" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "p2(x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#-%#p2G6#%\"xG" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 8 "p2(t-3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#-%#p2G6#,&%\"tG\"\"
\"\"\"$!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p2(u^3-u^2+
2);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#-%#p2G6#,(*$)%\"uG\"\"$\"\"\"F+
*$)F)\"\"#F+!\"\"F.F+" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "     " }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 255 "     This works just like we expect substituti
on to work because p2 is an operation on whatever is in the (  ).  How
ever since p1 is a symbolic expression we have some difficulties with \+
substituting into it directly.   Try the following command sequences.
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 6 "p1(x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6#F'\"\"#
\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 8 "p1(t-3);
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6#,&%\"tG\"\"\"\"\"$!\"
\"\"\"#F+F+F+F-" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p1(u^3-u
^2+2);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6#,(*$)%\"uG\"\"$
\"\"\"F.*$)F,\"\"#F.!\"\"F1F.F1F.F.F.F2" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 135 "      Notice the extra x in front
.  This is curious and not very reassuring.  To substitute into a symb
olic expression we must use the " }{TEXT 284 4 "subs" }{TEXT -1 9 " co
mmand." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "subs(x=t-3,p1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&
*$),&%\"tG\"\"\"\"\"$!\"\"\"\"#F(F(F(F*" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "subs(x=6,p1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"#N
