{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 280 111 "Why do you think high school students a
re never asked to remember the general formula for the roots of a cubi
c?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 11 "to complex?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 113 "4.  Solving Equations in
 One Variable.   There are two different commands to direct Maple to s
olve an equation:  " }{TEXT 285 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 
286 7 "fsolve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "They have different pur
poses.  The " }{TEXT 287 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 63 " command attempts to \+
find exact solutions.  If the expression  " }{TEXT 289 1 "f" }{TEXT 
-1 116 "  is defined in terms of only one variable, there are several \+
different ways to direct Maple to solve the equation  " }{TEXT 290 5 "
f  = " }{TEXT 291 4 "0.  " }{TEXT -1 54 "The following all cause Maple
 to solve the equation   " }{TEXT 292 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 293 2 "0." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 16 "       so
lve(f);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f,x);" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f=0);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
20 "       solve(f=0,x);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 349 "Maple makes an assumption that if the coefficient
s of a polynomial are all given exactly (as integers or rational numbe
rs [ratios of integer]), then you are only interested in finding exact
 solutions.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that
 the solutions of  a polynomial can be found exactly, only the polynom
ial has solutions.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 78 "You can force Maple to report additional (approximate) \+
solutions by using the " }{TEXT 288 6 "fsolve" }{TEXT -1 45 " command.
  (What does the \"f\" stand for?)  In" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
249 "addition, to forcing Maple to report approximate solutions, you c
an specify a field extension (typically real or complex) and require M
aple to look for solutions which fit in that field extension.  Also, o
ne can specify a range of x values and force" }{TEXT 296 7 " fsolve" }
{TEXT -1 75 " to only look for solutions in that specified range.  For
 example, compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "
> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "fsolve(4*x-x^3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6%$!+++++?!\"*$\"\"!F'$\"+++++?F%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "fsolve(4*x-x^3,x=1..4);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+++++?!\"*" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "For each of the polynomials " }{XPPEDIT 
18 0 "p[1]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"\"\"" }{TEXT -1 9 " through " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 
"p[14]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"#9" }{TEXT -1 19 ", do the following:" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "     a.   solve for all exact roots whereever pos
sible, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 59 "     b.   find all approximate
 roots to 10 decimal places, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 43 "     c. \+
 factor each into linear factors.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 106 "You will need to click on  [> in the to
olbar to obtain new execution lines just below the cursor position." }
